This paper discusses techniques for estimating parameters of probabilistic models of language, which is a topic that falls under the subfield of natural language processing (NLP) in computer science. The paper specifically focuses on two related strategies, noise contrastive estimation (NCE) and negative sampling, which are commonly used in NLP research. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.CL (Computation and Language). However, the paper also discusses the computational aspects of these techniques, which suggests that it may also be relevant to sub-categories such as cs.LG (Machine Learning), cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence), and cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing). Additionally, the paper mentions the use of negative sampling for learning word representations, which is a common task in computer vision research, so it may also be relevant to the sub-category cs.CV (Computer Vision).
